Of note - before the trees started dying about 5 years ago we assumed that this site was a perfect place for cedar. Also of note, when a tree dies it often does so very quickly - within a few months from healthy looking to dead.

column17:
I live in a HOA that has a greenbelt of about two hundred acres. Cedars that were large and healthy have been dying. We removed about eighty trees last year that suddenly died and we removed seventy more this year. This year the dead tree list also had hemlocks. I think we will lose all of our hemlocks soon and many, many of our cedars have thin tops, dead tops, or just up and died. The dead trees are of all sizes from a yard or more in diameter to ten inches. The die off started in the more moist areas of the greenbelt but is spreading. 
The greenbelt is in what is essentially a housing development but there are rules to protect trees. The ground varies from dry to wet. There are areas that probably should never have been platted due to wetness.  The ground has a gradual slope.

column66: Community park with well used trails. This tree was right next to the creek in a ravine. Mix of dead branches and thin canopy at the bottom of the tree, canopy gets fuller and thicker towards the top. Not sure if it's unhealthy, or if this is just normal branch dieback due to mature stand with tall trees and crowded upper canopy. Mix of Douglas Fir and Cedars. Majority of cedars in the immediate area are of similar size and condition (thin canopy/dead branches at the bottoms, full canopy at the top). Over 10 in similar condition nearby.

column66: Two trees appear to have expanded into each other at ground level. This observation is about the trunk on the right in photos with both trunks. The tops of all three trees show in the overall canopy photo; this observation is about the one in the center of that photo. Tree does not show any tip dieback. It appears to have normal dieback of interior shaded branches, shown in one photo. There is also one small branch in the canopy with dead leaves shown in a canopy photo; it is probably from something breaking it, not dieback from stress.

column66: This tree (as shown) was cut back for the sake of the path beneath its canopy. Otherwise, it appears to be fairly healthy. It is growing up a slope from a stream that flows with at least a trickle of water year round. There is little visible damage on this tree besides the trimming for the trail. As for other species' health, this forest is fairly healthy. There are very few dead snags besides those that have fallen in the recent windstorms we've been experiencing. However, I do believe that this forest could be at risk in the future due to the abundance of invasive himalayan blackberry and english ivy, which have choked out some native wildflower species. The ivy has started to climb nearby bigleaf maples, red alders, and douglas firs and should be removed to prevent harm to these trees.

column17:
For up to 3 years... we've noticed a dieback in the tops of an ever-increasing number of mature Western Redcedars in our immediate vicinity.
However, within the past year we've noticed that many trees in the immediate vicinity and the larger greater community (15mi radius) have redding/browning foliage and are NOT recovering. It is NOT just along roads and of particular note... even trees have or are very near to year-round visible surface water have been affected, however those with a south exposure and on ridges are severely affected.
We suspect the massive dieback was triggered by the heat dome of 2021 (persistent 113F) and exacerbated by drought over the last few years.
Dieback is also detected in a few firs and lodgepole pine... but NOT ubiquitous like the cedars.

column66: These trees are all on our property. Several have had dead canopies for 15 to 20 years and some are much newer. One old one is next to a road and a newer one is near our driveway and has some brownish leaf ends. We have a large area of wooded land that backs up to a King County open space. Several of the trees are in this area. There is a gentle slope to the land and it is quite wet in the winter months particularly. There's evidence of sap sucker around woodpecker holes on some of the trees. The big leave maple trees are in the process of dying or dead and there are a few firs that are dying and the bark is peeling. We have several Western road cedars that are enormous and would take many people to wrap arms around the base of the trunk..
